Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has provided all of its students with more sleep. This is an attempt to combat the growing culture of the steepness of learning all night long after refilling with caffeine.
The lecturer found that the number one university students in the world are often uneducated when it comes to the very basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Chaisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Women’s Hospital, has developed what he believes is the first such course in the U.S.
He decided to start the course after giving a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
At the end, a girl came up to him and said, “Why am I being told this now, in my final year?”
“She told me that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” the teacher told The Telegraph.
The course, which was first introduced this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help achieve academic and athletic outcomes, as well as improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s medical services, said the university decided to introduce the course after it was found that students were severely sleep deprived for a week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is an image of a dorm room where students click cups of coffee, curtains, exercise machines, and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, the effects of sleep deprivation on athletic performance, and the importance of a sleep-related routine.
In another section, participants are told how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Further, the campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know it won’t change students’ behavior instantly.
But we believe that they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know about the health effects of smoking cigarettes,” added Professor Cheisler.
A culture of pride in “sleepless nights” still exists, he added, and noted that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students mean that the problem of sleep deprivation is growing.
Getting enough good quality sleep should be a student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, even with weight gain, as sleep deprivation puts the brain into starvation mode, causing constant physical hunger, he said.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Cheysler design the course after enrolling in one of his other courses last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to create a new course for the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, will be to appeal to all graduate students with a request to undergo a similar training program before coming to a competitive institution.
Professor Chaisler recommends that students set a reminder to go to bed, set an alarm, and be aware of the harmful effects of blue light, which is emitted by electronic screens and LED lamps and can disrupt the circadian rhythm, leading to problems with falling asleep.
