Is the idea of rewarding an act with a free concert a brilliant way to convince people to take action, or is it just another case of so-called “clictivism” where people feel that they’re really making a difference by signing an e-petition or posting on Twitter?
According to Global Citizen, since 2011, they have recorded 19 million “deeds” of their supporters, aimed at achieving various goals.
According to the organization, these actions prompted world leaders to announce planned financial allocations and programs worth more than $ 37 billion, which by 2030 will help change the lives of more than 2.25 billion people.
In early 2018, the group cited 390 financial commitments and public statements as an example of its performance, with at least $10 billion already collected and spent.
According to the group, the funds have already directly affected the lives of approximately 649 million people worldwide.
Among the main financial commitments can be mentioned The Power of Nutrition fund, which is territorially related to the UK. As part of the project, investors and implementers have committed to "help children grow up" and promised to provide Rwanda with $ 35 million in aid to overcome the problem of malnutrition after receiving more than 4700 reports from Global Civit.
