The National Trust will observe the secret life of bats
A new study, which is being conducted on land in the Scottish Highlands, aims to establish how bats use the landscape in search of food.
Scientists hope that the data will help shed light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals in order to conduct conservation measures in the future.
In the gardens of Inveryu in Western Ross, scientists of the National Trust of Scotland will observe such species as the dwarf bat and the pygmy bat, as well as the common eared and water nightshade.
Special recorders will be placed in strategic locations on the land to monitor bat behavior throughout the season.
Employees and volunteers of the National Trust of Scotland will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
Expert analysis of all recorded sounds will help to determine the frequency and belonging of bat cries.
Then it is planned to develop a detailed map of the habitat of animals and prepare a report to link the behavior of animals with their habitat.
Rob Dewar, a conservation adviser at the National Trust of Scotland, hopes the findings will help determine which habitats are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to assess the effectiveness of habitat management measures (e.g. grassland formation) and identify optimal forest conservation practices for bats and other related species.
Over the last century, bat populations have declined significantly in Scotland and the United Kingdom.
They are threatened by active construction and development of territories, which deprives them of nesting places.
Other negative factors include wind installations and lighting, fly glue paper, chemical processing of building materials, and attacks of domestic cats.
They are not actually blind.
However, through hunting at night, the ears are more effective in helping them catch prey than the eyes.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to detect insects and obstacles on the flight path.
The National Trust of Scotland, which cares for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens of special importance and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, takes bat problems very seriously.
Ten specially trained experts regularly conduct research, check nesting sites and sometimes even rescue operations.
The organization even created the first and only bat reserve in Scotland. It is located on the territory of the Triv estate in the Dumfries and Galloway region. It sheltered eight of the ten species of bats living in Scotland.
The estate manager, David Thompson, says it’s the perfect place for them.
"On the territory of the estate lasted excellent conditions for bats", - he assures.
“There are old buildings, many giant trees and other favorable living conditions.
But we still have a lot to learn about bats, and thanks to the research we're doing here and elsewhere, we'll be able to learn more about what they need to thrive."
He insists that it is very important to check the territory for the presence of bats before carrying out any technical work, because due to the unintentional destruction of one nesting site for the removal of young can kill up to 400 females with cubs, which is likely to cause the destruction of the entire local population.
Bats and their nests are protected by law. Animals are forbidden to kill, torture or disturb.
Elizabeth Ferrell, an officer at Scotland’s Bat Conservation Centre, urged the public to join the organisation’s efforts.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats. We have not yet revealed the characteristics of populations of many species."
