Earthquakes and tsunamis in Indonesia
At least 384 people were killed in a powerful earthquake and tsunami in the Indonesian city of Palu on Friday, government officials said, but the death toll could rise.
Due to the failure of communications, officials dealing with humanitarian aid issues cannot obtain any information from the Dongala Regency, an area north of Palu that is closer to the epicenter of the 7.5-magnitude earthquake.
After the disaster, 16,000 people were evacuated from Palu.
Here are some basic facts about the city of Palu located on the island of Sulawesi and the regency of Dongala.
Palu is the capital of Central Sulawesi Province, located at the end of a narrow bay on the west coast of Sulawesi Island, with an estimated population of 379,800 people as of 2017.
When the earthquake that caused the tsunami occurred, the city celebrated its 40th anniversary.
Dongala is a regency that extends for more than 300 km (180 mi) along the coastline in the northwest of Sulawesi.
According to data for 2017, the regency, an administrative region located in the lower part of the province, is home to about 299,200 people.
Fisheries and agriculture are the main sectors of the economy of Central Sulawesi province, especially the coastal region of Dongala.
Nickel mining is also important in the province, but is mainly concentrated in Moroval, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
According to the Indonesian Disaster Mitigation Agency, Palu and Dongala have been hit by tsunamis several times over the past 100 years.
In 1938, a tsunami in Dongala killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes.
In 1996, a tsunami also hit the western part of Dongala, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located in the seismically active Pacific Ring of Fire and regularly suffers from earthquakes.
Below are some of the biggest earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years.
2004: On December 26, a strong earthquake on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh, located in northern Sumatra, caused a tsunami that hit 14 countries, killing 226,000 people along the coast of the Indian Ocean, most of them in Aceh province.
2005: In late March and early April, a series of powerful earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra.
Hundreds of people died on the island of Nias off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8-magnitude earthquake shook southern Java, Indonesia's most densely populated island, and caused a tsunami that hit the southern coast, killing about 700 people.
2009: An earthquake of magnitude 7.6 was recorded near Padang, the capital of West Sumatra Province.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: A 7.5-magnitude earthquake shook one of the Mentawai islands off Sumatra, causing a tsunami up to 10 meters high that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A weak earthquake struck the Pidijaya Regency in Aceh province, causing devastation and panic due to the fact that people had not yet managed to forget the devastating 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
This time there was no tsunami, but more than 100 people died under the rubble of buildings.
2018: Severe earthquakes hit the tourist island of Lombok in Indonesia, killing more than 500 people, mostly in the northern part of the island.
